article.description: Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 21 points, and the Los Angeles Sparks overcame a 19-point third-quarter deficit to beat the Sacramento Monarchs 96-88 in double-overtime Friday night.
article.headline: McWilliams-Franklin leads Sparks' comeback against Monarchs
article.linkText: Sparks rally from 19 down, top Monarchs in 2 OT
article.story:
LOS ANGELES -- Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 21 points and 10
rebounds as the Los Angeles Sparks rallied for a 96-88 victory in
double overtime over the Sacramento Monarchs on Friday night.

	   Sidney Spencer added 15 points and Mwadi Mabika, Marta Fernandez
and Sherill Baker scored 14 points apiece for the Sparks (6-5), who
broke a three-game losing streak.

	   Kara Lawson scored 20 points for the Monarchs (8-4), whose
three-game winning streak ended. Nicole Powell added 18 points and
a career-high 12 rebounds.

	   Los Angeles used two turnovers to take an 89-83 lead in the
second overtime. McWilliams-Franklin made a steal that turned into
Mabika's layin with 4:38 remaining and converted a shot-clock
violation into a follow shot with 3:55 to play.

	   "Our defense started getting together," Sparks coach Michael
Cooper said. "I thought we made them take a lot of tough shots and
when they started missing, we were finally able to rebound the ball
and get our fast break going."

	   Sacramento held a 21-point lead in the third quarter but Baker
forced overtime by making a free throw with 3.9 seconds left in the
fourth quarter.

	   "We had a great opportunity and we let it slip away," Lawson
said. "They were pounding us on the boards in the second half. We
went away from what we do well, and that's getting stops and
finishing plays."

	   The Monarchs built an 83-79 lead with 2:03 left in the first
overtime period but layins by Murriel Page and Spencer forced an
83-83 tie with 27.3 seconds left.

	   Sacramento committed 24 turnovers that led to 30 of the Sparks'
points.
